Vice President Mike Pence led a discussion with the chief executives of approximately 50 states, territories, and the city of Washington, DC, along with the White House Coronavirus Task Force. They discussed local, state, and federal coronavirus response and recovery best practices. Pence updated on COVID-19 response and discussed limiting the spread of the virus, including adhering to state and local guidelines and wearing face coverings when social distancing is not possible. The discussion also covered federal support for nursing homes, CDC guidance on reopening schools safely, and efforts to protect vulnerable citizens. The Department of Homeland Security's Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency will release updated guidance to include those who teach and support children. Ambassador Birx provided an update on trends and data and discussed her recent travels. Centers for Medicare & Medicaid Services Administrator Verma discussed actions to protect vulnerable populations and highlighted best practices in long-term care settings. CMS will require nursing homes to test staff weekly and advise testing twice per week in communities with high test positivity rates. Admiral Giroir provided an update on testing support in nursing homes, while Admiral Polowczyk provided an update on PPE supplies. Health and Human Services Secretary Alex Azar provided an update on Operation Warp Speed, which aims to deliver 300 million doses of a safe COVID-19 vaccine by the end of the year. CDC Director Robert Redfield provided an update on school reopening guidance. The Trump Administration has conducted nearly 340 briefings with over 155,000 participants since January 2020.